{"/service/ndnp/curiv/batch_curiv_roseheath_ver01/data/sn92070146/00414188849/1938020101/0543.xml":{"full_text":"2\nOptimistic Outlook\n-POST-PRESS PHOTO-ENGRAVING\nHounding a cheerful note in the California business outlook. H. L.\nFarrar, president of the Coast Counties Gas and Electric Co. visited\nImperial Valley last weekend. He is shown (right) conferring with\nRussell Nance, valley manager. Farrar said he believed the business\nrecession only temporary.\nNew Dealers Consider\nLoans to Small Business\nWASHINGTON, Feb 1. (UP) \u2014An administration plan\nto aid small business still was in the preliminary study\nstage today\u2014the day before a conference between com\nmerce department officials and more than 500 \u201clittle\u201d\nbusiness men. Hundreds of letters poured into the capital.\nofficials said, appealing for finan--<\ncial assistance to \u2018'little\" men in\ntheir fight against tne economic\nrecession.\nTomorrow and Thursday, between\n500 and 750 little business men will I\noutline their problems and make\nrecommendations.\nAdministration fiscal officials\ngenerally were in agreement that\nsome form of financial aid was\nvital.\nThe suggestions which appeared\nto have attracted most attention\nip administration circles included\ncreation of federal intermediate\nCredit banks to advance small loans\nto little business men or a national\nmortgage corporation which would\nguarantee loans made by commer\ncial banks.\nI\nCONSIDER\na Packard before you buy a\nCar Prices from $1291\nup in El Centro.\nJACK PERSSON\n732 Main Phone 821\nI\nBfc\n\"fieeiZhuufy, pm\ntou/td HSifafYc//\"\nMany mtn when away from\nhome make a practice of call\ning the family and keeping in\nclose touch. From 7 p. in.\nuntil 4:30 a.m., exceptionally\nattractive NIGHT rates are in\neffect to most long distance\npoints. They are also in effect\nall day Sundays.\nSOUTHERN CALIFORNIA TELEPHONE COMPANY\n042 State Street Telephone El C entro 800\nPHONE 300\n116 CARS OF\nLETTUCE GO\nTO MARKETS\nOne hundred sixteen cars of let-\ntuce were shipped from the valley i\nMonday to bring the season total\nto 4.458 cars\nTwenty-five cars of carrots were\nshipped to boost the season total j\nfor carrots to 396 cars.\nLettuce prices continued poor\nwhile carrot prices held moderately j\nhigh.\nHOG GROWERS\nMEET TONITE\nImperial Valley hog growers will\nmeet at the county court house to\nnight at 7:30 to discuss plans for a\nswine day to be held in the valley*\nthis spring.\nGeorge L. Winwright. assistant\ncounty agent, will be at the meeting\nto aid in the formation of plans.\nGeneral Strike on\nCanal Threatened\n(Continued from Page 1)\nHouse. Lewis-Chambers truck driv\ner. to serve a warrant charging\nHouse with disturoing the peace.\nJohn H Reese. Calexico tabor\nleader, signed a complaint charg\ning House with attacking A S.\nMendoza, labor union picket. The\nfight between Mendoza and House\nresulted Monday in action by the\nsheriff outsting all pickets from\ntheir positions on the Lewis-Cham\nbers job If House is convicted, said\nLouis Fabian, business agent tor\nthe common laborers' union, the\nunion will attempt to have him\njailed for violation of probation He\nis under probation on a recent\nforgery conviction.\nThe sheriff said Tcesday that la\nbor leaders had promised to send\nMendoza to talk to him about the\nfight, but that Mendoza had not\nappeared in his office late Tuesday.\nA direct bearing on the union\ndemand .or an increase from 45\ncents to 62\u2019a cents an hour tor\ncommon laborers may develop in\na hearing at the U. S. reclamation\nbureau office in Calexico at 10\na.m. Wednesday when Bertram R.\nCoen, special referee, conducts an\ninquiry for the U. S. department\nof labor to determine prevailing\nwage rates which should be paid\nmechanics and laborers on the All\nAmerican canal.\nCanal contractors are required\nby the federal government to pay\nprevailing wage scales.\nLabor leaders professed a desire\nto end the strike as rapidly as pos-\nsible. pointing out that Stewart\nMeecham, field examiner for the\nNational Labor Relations Board,\nwas scheduled to confer with Lewis\nChambers executives late Tuesday\nlin an effort to bring about an\ni agreement. Meecham has spent the\nlast several days interviewing\nI strikers.\nLarger Scale\n\u201cWe are going to attempt to\ncome to a satisfactory conclusion\nof the strike today,\" said Fabian.\nbut unless Lewis-Chambers capi\nt ulates at least to a small degree,\nwe see no other alternative than\nto keep this strike going on an\nj even larger scale.\u201d\nWhile company executives an\nnounced that work on their con\ni tracts is going ahead normally with\nfull crews on the job. Fabian de\n-1 clared that 98 per cent of the\nunion men on the job remained\non strike. Those still working are\neither non-union men or men who\nwill lose their union cards, he said.\nCompany executives reported\nTuesday 142 men were at work on\nthe job, compared to 127 the day\nthe strike was called.\nThe sheriff said Tuesday that la\nwith about SIOOO a week when Yu\nma carpenters voted a $1 a day as\nsessment against themselves last\nweek, was swelled to greater pro\nportions Monday night when Im\nperial Valley members of the car\npenters\u2019 union voted a similar as\nsessment to support the strike.\nStormy Weather\nGrips West Coast\n(Continued from Page 1)\novercast skies carried the promise of\nadditional precipitation.\nThe rain, which totaled .06 of an\ninch in El Centro ceased before\nnoon. Heavy cloudiness is expected\nto prevail in the valley for several\ndays. Woodrow C. Jacobs, meteor\nologist. said.\nAt noon Tuesday the temperature\nwas 58 degrees with the humidity 88\nAt 5 a.m. the temoerature was 55\ndegrees and humidity 59.\nTemperatures at the colder sta\ntions in the valley ranged from 30\nto 35 degrees during the last several\ndays, Jacobs said, but only slight\ndamage to tender vegetables was\nreported. Low clouds and gentle\nto moderate southerly winds will\ndispell any threat of further frost\nuntil the storm passes, about Wed\nnesday.\nAll valley towns reported light\nsprinkles beginning shortly after 8\no'clock and continuing until noon.\nAgriculture suffered slight dam\nage. Lettuce cutting was slowed\nwith other crops unaffected.\nSAN DIEGO, Cal., Feb 1. (UP)\n\u2014Heavy rains, driven by strong,\ngusty winds swept San Diego coun\nty today.\nAt 8 a.m., the weather bureau\nreported a 24-hour precipitation of\n.34 inches.\nNo snow was reported although\nback-country mountain areas were\n(receiving heaivy rainffal], which\npromised to turn to snow as the\ntemperature fell sharply at Julian\nand Pine Valley.\nHeaviest rainfall in the area was\nreported at Escondido, with .95\ninches. La Jolla had .83 inches;\nOceanside .77 inches; Del Mar .60\ninches; Coronado 44 inches; La\nMesa .35 inches and Chula Vista\nand Alpine .30 inches.\nBy UNITED PRESS\nWinter\u2019s severest cold wave, which\ntumbled temperatures below zero\nin the north central states, loosed\nits hold and moved north\neastward into Ontario.\nThe mercury began a slow rise\nthroughout the Mississippi and\nOhio valleys. U. S. Forecaster J.\nR. Lloyd said the wave practically\nwas ended in the middle west.\nJOO OLD FOR SI K IDE\nCLEVELAND, (UP) Joseph\nPopk, 54. was in ill health and had\nno money. He jumped from a pier\nintb Lake Erie. The water was icy\ncold from winter winds\u2014too cold\nfor suicide. Popk changed his mind,\nshouted for help and was rescued\nby a steamship captain, Luther\nImperial Valley Press\nEntaMlnbed AurV 20, 1901.\nevery nftrmuun except\nMaturaay and Suuduy (.Saturday\nuftrrutHfu laaue now succeeded by\nIbe Po\u00abt Pre mm Sunday rMfahllmb\ned 19.36) by the Imperial Valley\nPubllabltiK toiapauy, <125 State\nafreet. El eutro, allf.\nEntered at El t'entro, California\npuwf o/fire nn aeeoud rlaan matter.\nPaul Jenklna, pabliMberf A. C.\nJohnston, vlee-president and cen\ntral luanagrri E. A. Fitzhugh,\nsecretary and manaiflng editor.\nWest-Holliday Co., Inc., National\n%d*ertiMlns Kepresenla fives.\nMembers allfornia Newspaper\nPublishers* Association.\nSubscription Rates: Sc per ropy.\nIn eon junction with the l*ost-\nPreas (Sundays), per month, fiOrj\nPaid In adtuutr; 3 months Si .65,\ntt mouths, *3.25; use year *6.00.\nIMPERIAL VALLEY PRESS, EL CENTRO, CALIF.\nPlump, Blue-Eyed Girl Born to\nNetherlands Princess Juliana\nSOESTDYK. Netherlands. Feb.\n1. (I\u2019P) A plump, blue-eyed\nbaby girl, born to crown prin\ncess Juliana early today in the\nwhite \"Honeymoon Palace\u201d of\nScestdyk, tonight slept placidly\nin a nursery her crib near\na large wall map showing the\ntrnpire ever which she may some\nday rule.\nThe sturdy daughter, born at\n9:4* A. M. as thousands waited\noutside the palace gates beneath\neven act skies, may carry into\nthe third generation the line of\nqueens reigning over the Nether\nlands Empire.\nI\u2019nless a sen is born to the\n28-year-old Juliana and her\nPrince (Consort. Bernhard Zu\nLippe Biesterfield. the child will\nfollow her mother in the line of\nsuccession to the throne of\nOrange-Nassau.\nThe baby. Juliana\u2019s first born,\nbecomes the Princess of Orange-\nNassau Zu Lippe Biesterfield. At\nINSTALLMENTOF ENGINEER DATA\nON DISTRICT CONDITION GIVEN\nContinued from Page One)\nin Imperial Irrigation District. An\nintake structure was built on the\nright bank of Colorado river just\nabove the International boundary\nthrough which water was taken\nfrom the river without a diversion\ndam. The canal from this point\nto Imperial Valley could not be\nbuilt through the United States\nbecause the sand hills east of Im\nperial Valley constituted a barrier\nwhich could not be overcome with\nthe resources and facilities then\navailable.\nThrough Mexico\nNot far below the headworks,\nhowever, the Alamo overflow chan\nnel took off from the river and\nfollowed a course through Mexico\ninto the Imperial Valley. This was\na natural route for the canal and\naccordingly a concession was ob\ntained from the Mexican govern\nment for its use and for the con\nstruction of irrigation works in\nMexico. A Mexican company was\norganized to build and operate this\npart of the irrigation system, and\nthe successor of this company still\nexists and is known as the Com\npania de Terrenos y Aguas de la\nBaja California, S. A.\nCalifornia Development Co., did\nnot construct the distribution can\nals for delivery of water to farm\ners, but this was done by a number\nof Mutual Water companies who\npurchased water from California\nDevelopment Co. Almost from the\ntime of the first deliveries in 1901,\nit was difficult to keep the head\nworks free of silt, and at times of\nlow flow in Colorado river enough\nwater could not be diverted to\nmeet all demands. In an effort to\nremedy this situation, the company,\na few years later, built new head\ngates in Mexico a short distance\nbelow the boundary, but with dis\nastrous results.\nA series of floods came down\nGila river\u2014which enters the Col\norado a few miles upstream\u2014and\nthe new headgate structure was\nwashed out. The full flow of Col\nlorado river then turned from its\nformer channel into the Alamo\ninto the Salton Sea. With its limit\ned resources, California Develop\nment Co. was unable to close the\nbreak, and intervention of tne\nUnited States was sought because\nof the tremendous damage being\ndone to lands in the valley, and\nbecause great erosion channels had\nformed which threatened to cut\nback up the river and destroy La\nguna dam.\nRailway Got Job\nThe actual task of closure was\ngiven to Southern Pacific Railroad\nCo., whose tracks across the Sal\nton Sink had been inundated. The\ntransportation facilities of the rail\nroad were diverted to this work,\nand finally the river turned back\ninto its fomer course. In the settle\nment of its claim the Southern\nPacific became the owner of Cali\nfornia Development Co., and its\nMexican subsidiary, and retained\npossession until 1916.\nThe people in Imperial Valley\nwere naturally desirous of owning\ntheir own irrigation works, and ac\ncordingly organized Imperial Ir\nrigation District July 25, 1911 for\nthis purpose. The district originally\nincluded a total area of 605,000\nacres, extending from the Interna\ntional boundary to the Salton Sea,\nwithin which were located all of\nthe Mutual Water companies.\nThe first issue of bonds of Im\nperial Irrigation District was au\nthorized by an election on Oct. 29,\n1914. These were in the amount of\n$3,500,000 and were to provide funds\ntor the purchase of the irrigation\nsystems of California Development\nCo. and its subsidiary. Actually,\nthese were not taken over until\n1916, after which the district oper\nated the diversion works on Colo\nrado river and the Mexican canal\nsystem much as had its predeces\nsors.\nElections Held\nWithin a few years there was\nagitation for the district to acquire\nthe distributing systems of the\nMutual Water companies, and elec\ntions were held at which bond issues\naggregating $12,500,000 were voted\nConvent Life Portrayed\nConvent life has for years been the subject of much conjecture.\nTo the average life-loving, worldly man and woman, it presents a\nproblem that is unfathomable, for, when convent doors clang shut,\nit means almost certain renunciation of all the things that they hold\nmost dear to them. Yet, to the girl or woman who seeks spiritual\nhappiness and peace within convent walls, the lite there is neither\ntedious nor anything but beautiful.\nFor the first time in two thousand years, the mystery of convent\nlife is being revealed to the laymen, and it comes to them through\nthe medium of motion pictures. \"Cloistered,\u201d the great success which\nis coming to the United Artists theatre on Thursday Feb. for one day\nonly, is the true picture of convent life. It was made in its entirety\nat the Convent of the Good Shepherd, and, since it brings to the\npublic great hidden truths about convent life, it was, of course, neces\nsary to gain the permission of the Vatican authorities before the\nfilm could be produced.\na formal cegemony today she\nwill be named probably Emma\nfor her grandmother and Juliana\nfor her mother.\nQueen Wilhelmina of the Neth\nerlands. so overjoyed that she\nburst into tears and hugged the\nexcited Prince Bernhard, ordered\na public holiday.\nThe camions of military gar\nrisons- spread the glad tidings\nwith 51-gun salutes from Ams\nterdam to Borneo.\nIn a proclamation, scattered by\nthousands of leaflets from low\nswooping airplanes, the queen\nannounced that \"Hereby the\nhearts\u2019 desire of all the Nether\nlands people has been realized\nThe birth of a daughter ful\nfilled Juliana\u2019s longing for she\nrecently wrote a woman friend\nthat:\n\"I know Bernhard and the na\ntion very much hope it will be a\nbey. but as for myself l'd love\nit to be a girl.\u201d\ntor this and other purposes. The\nMutual Water companies were ac\nquired in 1928 and 1923, and the\ndistrict has since then carried on\nall functions of diversion, trans\nportation. and delivery of water in\nImperial Valley.\nNo additional bonds of the dis\ntrict have been authorized, other\nthan refunding bonds, but exten\nsions and betterments have been\nmade out of operatig revenue until\ntoday the books of the district show\nalmost $20,000,000 of fixed assets.\nPresent Fixed Assets\nA recent condensed balance sheet\nof Imperial Irrigation District car\nries the following items of fixed\nassets:\nCanal System. Additions\nand Betterments 10.262,010\nProtective Works\u2014 Flood\nControl 3.873,910\nDrainage Canals and\nStructures 2,762,270\nLaguna Dam Diversion\nRight 1,415,385\nBuildings, Less Depre-\nciation 247,965\nLand 143,693\nEquipment and Facili-\nties, less depreciation 475,237\nOther Assets 482,877\nTotal Fixed Assets\nAugust 31. 1937 19.633,347\nThe largest item above is for\nthe canal system and additions\nand betterments. Most of the\nsystem was acquired by purchase\nfrom California Development Co.\nand from the Mutual Water com\npanies, but material betterments\nand extensions have been made\nduring the past fifteen years.\nThe expenditures for protective\nworks have been largely for levees\nin Mexioo which have kept the\nfloods of Colorado river from again\nflowing into Imperial Valley. The\ntotal of $3,873,910 is presumably\nexclusive of amounts expended by\nthe United States and may not\nreflect all of the expenditures made\nby the predecessor companies for\nflood control.\nThe district has constructed,\nout of bond funds and to some\nextent from operating revenue\na partial system of outlet and\nsurface drains, which are used\nprimarily for carrying off waste\nirrigation waters. The outlet\ndrains are deep channels which\ngenerally discharge into New\nriver or Alamo river, the principal\nchannels eroded at the time Col\norado river broke into the valley.\nThe surface drains are relatively\nshallow and must be deepened\nbefore they can function as\ndrains.\nLaguna dam diversion right rep\nresents payments which have been\nmade to the United States under\na contract entered into in 1918.\nwhereby Imperial Irrigation Dis\ntrict was granted the right of con\nnection to Laguna dam, the point\nof diversion for the Yuma Valley.\nThe new diversion dam, Impe\nrial dam, being built is located\nabove Laguna dam; consequently,\nthe $1,415,385 Laguna dam div\nersion right has no real present\nvalue except as it influenced the\nconditions of payment for the\nnew works being built by United\nStates for the district.\nNEW WORKS\nThe United States, through the\nBureau of Reclamation, recently\ncompleted Boulder dam and the\nflood waters of Colorado river are\nnow being stored in Lake Mead\nThe water supply of the district\nis thereby assured and the flood\nmenace has been reduced.\nThe Bureau of Reclamation is\nalso building, as part of the Boulde.\nCanyon project, a new diversion\ndam on Colorado river about fif\nteen miles above the mouth of\nGila river, together with a very\nlarge canal from there to the Im\nperial Valley. The latter Is called\nthe All American canal and, as\nthe name implies is being built in\nthe United States for its entire\nlength. The construction cost is to\nbe repaid by Imperial Irrigation\ndistrict under the terms and con\nditions of the All-American canal\ncontract entered into Dec. 1, 1932.\nWhen the Imperial dam and All\nChurch to Hold\nSilver Jubilee\nPlans for the Silver Jubilee cele\nbration. commemorating the 25th\nanniversary of the establishment of\nSt. Mary's Catholic church in El\nCentro, were rushed toward com\npletion Tuesday, according to Father\nVan Veggel.\nA jubilee mass and dinner are\nplanned Sunday. Feb. 13, and Bishop\nBuddy, of the San Diego and Im\nperial county diocese, will be in\nthe valley for the occasion.\nInvitations have been sent to all\npriests who have served in the St.\nMary's church since its establish\nment. Father Van Veggel said.\nC. of C. Directors\nWill Entertain\nS.D Visitors Wed.\nDirectors of the El Centro Cham\nber of Commerce will entertain the\nSan Diego city council, headed by\nRobert M. Flack, city manager, at\na breakfast at the Barbara Worth\nhotel Wednesday morning.\nThe San Diego group toured the\nAll American canal and Imperial\ndam Tuesday.\nAmerican canal are completed, the\ndiversion works at the Internation\ni al boundary below Yuma and the\ncanals in Mexico will be no longer\nuseful for delivery of water to\nlands in the United States, but\nsuch diversion works and canals\nwill still be of value for delivery\nof water to lands in Mexico.\nThe disposition to be made of\nthe canal system and other works\nin Mexico is not known at this\ntime, but it is assumed that the\nCoinpania will continue to func\ntion as in the past until the title\nto the property is passed to the\nMexican government, either in\naccordance with the concession\nunder which these works have\nbeen operated, or in accordance\nwith a treaty which probably will\nbe entered into between Mexico\nand the United States.\nThe All-American canal is be\ning built large enough to serve the\nCoachella Valley at the northerly\nend of the Salton Sea and large\ndesert areas on the mesas to the\neast and west of the irrigated por\ntion of Imperial Valley. The Coach\nella region will presumably not\nbecome a part of Imperial Irriga\ntion District, but the lands on the\nEast Mesa and on the West Mesa\nmust be brought into the district\nwithin a reasonable period of time.\nPower Plants\nProvision has been made in the\nconstruction of All-American canal\nfor the installation of hydro-elec\ntric power plants at several points\nalong its course. In the years oi\nnegotiation which preceded con\nstruction of this canal, the poten\ntialities of revenue from the sale\nof power were an important ele\nment.\nFinally, in anticipation of the\nhydro-electric power to become\navailable, Imperial Irrigation Dis\ntrict built a diesel-electric gener\nating plant at Brawley, and in\nMay, 1936 commenced delivery of\npower in competition with the\npublic utility company which here\ntofore had had a virtual monopoly.\nLater, the district obtained funds\nfrom Public Works administration\nfor the enlargement of this diesel\nelectric plant and for the construc\ntion of one hydro-electric plant on\nAll-American canal. It is now en\ngaged in the construction of \u25a0an\nelectrical distribution system thru\nout the valley under contract with\nthe Rural Electrification adminis\ntration; and it is expected that\nthe district will be in full competi\ntion with the public utility com\npany within a year.\nHistorical conditions of operation\nare thus being changed radically.\nThe costs of operation and the\nrevenues which were customary in\nthe past may differ widely from\nthose in the future. The indebted\nness is being trebled and annual\nfixed charges greatly increased.\nConsequently, the ability of tne\ndistrict to meet its obligations can\nnot be judged solely from past\nperformance, and in the following\nchapters of this report we have\nset forth the principal factors\nwhich lead us to the conclusion\nthat adjustment of the burden of\nImperia) Irrigation District is ne\ncessary.\nYOU haven\u2019t read ALL the NEWS\nuntil you READ the AILS!\n-t-- j in-- 1\nAttention\nImperial Valley\nResidents\nThe American Federation of Labor\nurges you to attend its open meeting\nat Wilson school, El Centro, Wednes\nday, Feb. 2 at 7:30 o\u2019clock.\nMany prominent civic and labor\nleaders are scheduled to speak under\nthe auspices of the Imperial Valley\nCentral Labor council.\nERNEST MILLER, President\nI). E. COOPER, Secretary\n\u20147 r\u2014- I..mi\nMilk Essay Winners\nin inWMMtmmiii' S\u25a0'>\nPOST-PRESS PHOTO-ENGRAVING\nTwo Imperial Valley children, winners in a recent essay contest\nsponsored by the Milk Institute during celebration of national milk\nweek. They are shown with two members of the institute. Left to\nright: D. V. Stewart. Helen Carleton of Imperial, .1. B. McNeece jr. of\nEl Centro, and Walter MacDonald, milk inspector.\nFARM BUREAU TAX GROUP TO\nADVISE CUTTING BOND DEMAND\nMembers of the Imperial County\nFarm Bureau tax committee will\nask Imperial Irrigation District\nbondholders to scale down both\nprincipal amount and interest rate.\nThis decision was made late Mon\nday afternoon, following a session\nover which Otto J. Bradshaw, tax\ncommittee chairman, presided. How\nard P Meyer of El Centro was des\nignated to present the matter for\nthe committee at a meeting with\nbondholders Friday in Los Angeles.\nEngineers' and auditors\u2019 reports,\nprepared under sponsorship of a\nbondholders\u2019 committee, were pre\nsented to the committee for its con\nsideration.\nMajority of the committee mem\nbers argued that in the light of the\nengineers' report and the economic\noutlook at large, it would be im\npossible to continue to pay assess\nments equal to the 1937-38 levy and\nthat if the district is to maintain\nits system, improve drainage and\nmeet its obligations, a much greater\nreduction in debt service than pro-\nFiery Plea Made\nIn Bond Hearing\n(Continued from Page 1)\nnot be used for any other purpose.\nHe said the court could not say\nthat the bondholders had the right\nto the money and then refuse them\npermission to collect it.\n\u201cThe district is attempting to\nthrow all its troubles in the lap of\nthe court and force all creditors to\naccept what others are willing to\naccept.\u201d Childers concluded.\nJudge Wilson took a mass of legal\npapers for consideration along with\ncases cited by the attorneys. He\ngave no indication as to when his\ndecision would be forthcoming.\nlIUBAN CLOVER SEED\nExcellent cover crop for citrus and\ngeneral crops. Immediate delivery.\nMARSHALL SEED FEED CO.\n120 So. Sixth St. Phone 35\n_\n\nYOU BE THE JUDGE!\nOf Our Expert Service Q\non\nRadiators 6 Ignition\nSpeedometers 9 Carburetors\nu IT\ne Motor Re-Winding \u2018I 1 1 I\n670 SAP RIIQI4 phone\nBroadway JvzL DUOIZI 644\nTUESDAY, FEBRUARY 1, 1938.\nvided in the 1937 assessment would\nbe necessary.\nEvan T. Hewes, district chair\nman, told the committee he be\nlieves a refunding agreement could\nbe worked out with the bondholders,\nby which unpaid interest would be\nwaived, $700,060 would be provided\nfor immediate drainage, if new\nbonds at par, 4 per cent, wen\nissued to take up the old bonds.\nPresent at the meeting, which\ncontinued until 5 o'clock, were\nChairman Bradshaw, Secretary\nScott Foulds, Charles Wieman, Les\nlie McConnell, J. E. Harshman, Capt.\nW. J. Gregg, Marcus Bates. Ernest\nV. Edwards, Frank Kumberg, A. O.\nDolson, C. G. Halliday, Charles E.\nSones, F. F. Pollard of the commit\ntee, and Hewes.\nWEATHER\nIlHitii complied by ohnervera for\nthe official United States weather\nbureau MtiUlun at KI Centro.)\nMaximum Monday 66\nMinimum Tuesday 42\nReading at Noon Tuesday\nTemperature 58\nHumidity 88\nReading at 5 a.m Tuesday\nTemperature 55\nHumidity 59\nReading at 5 p.m Monday\nTemperature 58\nHumidity 56\nYOU haven\u2019t read ALL the NEWS\nuirtil you READ the ADS!\nR. K. McLean, M.D.I\nEys Ear Nose Throat\n203 Rehkopf Bldg\nTelephone 566\nHours: 10-12, 2-5\nAnd By Appointment\ni..","height":"29636","width":"22876"}}
